ast tells the colorful story of this legendary period in France. Richard Wolin shows how French students and intellectuals, inspired by their perceptions of the Cultural Revolution, and motivated by utopian hopes, incited grassroots social movements and reinvigorated French civic and cultural life.Wolin’s riveting narrative reveals that Maoism’s allure among France’s best and brightest actually had little to do with a real understanding of Chinese politics. Instead, it paradoxically served as a vehicle for an emancipatory transformation of French society. Recounting the cultural and political odyssey of French students and intellectuals in the 1960s, The Wind from the East illustrates how the Maoist phenomenon unexpectedly sparked a democratic political sea change in France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCommunismzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aIntellectualsxPolitical activityzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aIntellectualszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAlain Badiou.  aAlgerian War.  aAtavism.  aAuthoritarianism.  aBolsheviks.  aBourgeoisie.  aCapitalism.  aCatechism.  aCharles de Gaulle.  aCivil society.  aClass conflict.  aClaude Lefort.  aCommunism.  aCommunist Party of China.  aComrade.  aCriticism.  aCultural Revolution.  aDaniel Cohn-Bendit.  aDictatorship.  aDissident.  aEmancipation.  aEthos.  aEveryday life.  aExistentialism.  aFeminism (international relations).  aFeminism.  aFrench Communist Party.  aFrench Left.  aGaullism.  aGay liberation.  aHomosexuality.  aIdentity politics.  aIdeology.  aImperialism.  aIndividualism.  aIndustrial society.  aInstitution.  aIntellectual.  aJacques Lacan.  aJean-Paul Sartre.  aJews.  aJulia Kristeva.  aLate capitali